Overview of PKI and Certificate Management Concepts:






Digital Signature

*use the asymmetric key algorithms to provide data integrity

*a specific signature function is added to the asymmetric algorithm at the senders side to digitally sign the message and a specific verification to ensure message integrity at the recipient side

*the asymmetric algorithms that support these two functions are called digital signature algorithms

*digitally signing messages slows the performance of during verification; the hash value of the message is used instead of the message itself for better performance

*a digital signature is created using the hash code of the message, the private key of the sender, and the signature function

*it is then verified using the hash code of the message, the public key of sender, and the verification function







Perfect Forward Secrecy (PFS)

*PFS is a cryptographic technique that protects previously encrypted session data against unintended decryption, even if the private key of the server is compromised

*it employs key exchanging algorithms such as Diffie-Hellman (DH) key exchange to generate a unique session key (ephemeral key) for each session initiated between the client and server; the key can be used only for that specific session








Digital Certificate Standard: X.509

*X.509 is the most widely used digital certificate

*in the X.509 system, a certification authority issues a certificate binding a public key to a particular distinguished name. A distinguished name is a unique name such as an email address or a domain name

*a distinguished name contains information about the certificate holder and signature of the entity that issued the certificate









Digital Certificate Formats

*Distinguished Encoding Rules (DER), is a binary encoding for both certificates and private keys, and the encoded files have the extensions .der and .cer

*Privacy Enhanced Mail (PEM), file consists of Base64 encoded ASCII data with the extensions .crt, .pem, .cer, and .key

*Personal Information Exchange (PFX), also referred to as PKCS#12, is a binary format to store a main host certificate and derived intermediate certificate with an associated private key in an encrypted file

*CER, files are security files issued by a third party CA to check website authenticity

*P7B, or PKCS#7 format employs Base64 ASCII encoding and uses the file extensions .p7b and .p7c

*PKCS#8, format consists of private keys and securely encrypted private key data with the extension .p8









Public Key Infrastructure (PKI)

*is a set of hardware, software, people, policies, and procedures required for creating, managing, distribution, using, storing, and revoking digital certificates







Components of a PKI

*a certificate authority (CA) that issues and verifies digital signatures

*a registration authority (RA) that acts as the verifier for the CA

*a certificate management system for generation, distribution, storage, and verification of certificates

*one or more directories where the certificates (along with their public keys) are stored









PKI Trust Models

*a trust model is a set of rules or constraints that instruct a client application on how to verify the authenticity of digital certificates

*Peer to Peer Trust Model, clients depend on their local CA, which serve as a starting point

*it is useful for small organizations

*Hybrid Trust Model, it is a combination of peer to peer and hierarchical trust models. the root CAs perform peer to peer tasks by sharing public keys. the intermediate CAs trust only their respective root CAs and other intermediate CAs within the hybrid environment

*Bridge Trust Model, it reduces the number of cross-certificates needed to be associated with PKIs. in a bridge CA, one CA servers as a central hub for connecting all other CAs and acts as a communication medium for them

*Web of Trust (WOT), is a trust model of PGP, OpenPGP, and GnuPG systems. everyone in the network is a certificate authority (CA) and sign s for other trusted entities. WoT is a network chain in which individuals act as intermediaries to validate each other's certificates using their signatures. every user in the network has a ring of public keys to encrypt data, and they introduce many other users whom they trust








Types of Digital Certificates

*Wildcard, a wildcard certificate can be configured to a domain and all its subdomains to minimize the complexity and cost

*Subject Alternative Name (SAN), a SAN certificate is used to protect multiple websites with a single SSL certificate

*Code Signing, it is a certificate that consists of a digital signature and is used to sign executables or scripts used in code to prove the identity of the developer or publisher

*Self-Signed, a certificate signed by the person or company that created it, instead of a trusted certificate authority

*Machine/Computer, also known as a computer certificate is generated at the time of activation of a computer









Internet Key Exchange (IKE)

*IPsec relies on IKE for secure key exchange and authentication

*IKE establishes security associations (SAs) to share security parameters such as digital certificates, pre shared keys, cipher algorithms, and key sizes







The negotiation of the IKE SA is performed in the following two phases:

*Phase 1, the IKE establishes a secure channel between two hosts using the Diffie-Hellman key exchange algorithm for the hosts to authenticate each other by sharing the private secret key and to encrypt the commination.

*Phase 2, the hosts use the previously created secure channel to negotiate SA security parameters to be used with IPsec








Certificate Revocation List (CRL) and Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP)

*Certificate Revocation List (CRL), is the list of all revoked certificates used for checking the certificate status. CAs maintain the CRL database, which stores all the suspended and revoked certificates

*Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP), also known as online revocation check, is an alternative to CRL for checking the status of certificate revocation. The OCSP responder at the CA checks the certificate's unique serial number to determine the certificate status









Certificate Stapling

*is an alternative version of the common OCSP method to determine the revocation status of SSL Certificates. A web server running SSL/TLS caches the time stamped OSCP responses from the CA. When a client sends an OCSP request, instead of the CA, the web server responds with a time stamped response from its cached records









